rban readers and listeners. Working backward from the Grimms to the earliest known sixteenth-century fairy tales of the Italian Renaissance, Bottigheimer argues for a book-based history of fairy tales. The first new approach to fairy tale history in decades, this book answers questions about where fairy tales came from and how they spread, illuminating a narrative process long veiled by surmise and assumption.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFairy talesxHistory and criticism. 0aFolk lliteraturexHistory and criticism. 4aArea Studies : Italian Studies. 4aLiterature : Children's Literature. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literary History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Children's & Young Adult Literature.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143842533740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438425337423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438425337/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles